I am going to get the source codes of frontend and backend of Telegram. Where can I get from?
ChatGPT said:

You can get the official source code for both the frontend (Telegram apps) and backend (Telegram server) from the following repositories:

Frontend (Telegram Apps)

Telegram's official apps are open-source, and you can find their source code on GitHub:

  • Android: https://github.com/Telegram-FOSS-Team/Telegram-FOSS (FOSS version)
  • iOS: https://github.com/TelegramMessenger/Telegram-iOS
  • Desktop (Windows, macOS, Linux): https://github.com/telegramdesktop/tdesktop
  • Web Apps:
    • WebK (Modern Web App): https://github.com/telegramdesktop/telegram-web-k
    • WebZ (Another Web Version): https://github.com/zhukov/webogram

Backend (Telegram Server)

Telegram's server (MTProto and backend infrastructure) is not open-source, so you cannot access its source code. Telegram only provides the MTProto protocol documentation:

  • MTProto Protocol Docs: https://core.telegram.org/mtproto
  • TDLib (Telegram Database Library, for bot & client development): https://github.com/tdlib/td

If you are looking for a self-hosted alternative, you may consider third-party Telegram-like projects such as MadelineProto or MTProxy.

🛠 Step-by-Step Guide to Build a Customized Chat System from Telegram's Source Code

🔹 Step 1: Understand How Telegram’s Architecture Works

Telegram uses:
✅ TDLib (Telegram Database Library) – A core library for handling messages, encryption, and network requests.
✅ MTProto Protocol – Secure communication protocol for messages.
✅ Telegram Backend – Normally, clients connect to Telegram’s servers, but you will replace this with your own backend.

Your main goal is to detach from Telegram's servers and create your own backend.

🔹 Step 2: Set Up Your Development Environment

1️⃣ Install Dependencies

Make sure you have the required tools installed on your system:

  • Android Studio (Latest version)
  • Gradle (Should be installed via Android Studio)
  • CMake & Ninja (For compiling TDLib)
  • OpenSSL & zlib (For encryption)

If you're on Windows, install these via MSYS2 or WSL.

2️⃣ Compile TDLib

Since Telegram’s Android app relies on TDLib, compile it for your system:

sh
mkdir tdlib_build && cd tdlib_build
cmake -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release -DTd_ENABLE_TESTS=OFF -G "Ninja" ..
ninja

This generates the required TDLib binaries, which you'll integrate into your app.

🔹 Step 3: Modify the Telegram Android App Source Code

Now that you have Telegram’s Android source code, modify it to remove bot functionality and connect to your own backend.

1️⃣ Remove Bot Functionality

To disable bot features:

  • Modify TDLib configurations
    In TdApi.java (inside TDLib), look for bot-related methods and disable them.
  • Disable bot login & commands
    Remove UI elements that handle bot commands in ChatActivity.java.

2️⃣ Change API & Authentication

  • Telegram uses an API_ID and API_HASH to connect to its backend.
  • Modify org.telegram.messenger.BuildVars.java:
    java
    public static final int APP_ID = YOUR_OWN_ID; // Change this
public static final String API_HASH = "YOUR_OWN_HASH"; // Change this
    This makes your app unique.

3️⃣ Remove Telegram Cloud Dependencies

By default, Telegram syncs messages via its own cloud servers.

  • Modify TDLib to store chat history locally or on your own backend.
  • Disable Telegram Cloud sync features in MessagesController.java.

🔹 Step 4: Set Up Your Own Backend

Since you want a private chat system, you must replace Telegram's backend with your own.

1️⃣ Backend Choices

  • Node.js + Express + WebSockets (Recommended for real-time messaging)
  • GoFiber (Golang) + WebSockets (For high-speed performance)
  • Django/Python + Django Channels (If you prefer Python)

2️⃣ Database for Storing Messages

  • PostgreSQL (Structured chat storage)
  • MongoDB (Flexible, easy to scale)
  • Redis (For real-time chat caching)

3️⃣ Implement WebSockets for Real-time Messaging

Instead of using Telegram’s servers, implement a WebSocket server:

javascript
const WebSocket = require("ws");
const server = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 8080 });

server.on("connection", (ws) => {
  ws.on("message", (message) => {
    console.log("Received: ", message);
    ws.send("Message received: " + message);
  });
});

Your modified Telegram app will now communicate with your WebSocket server instead of Telegram's servers.

🔹 Step 5: Modify TDLib to Work with Your Backend

To make your Telegram Android client talk to your backend instead of Telegram’s servers, modify TDLib’s network requests:

  • Open TdJsonClient.cpp in the TDLib source code.
  • Replace Telegram’s API URLs with your backend’s API.

Example:

cpp
const std::string TELEGRAM_SERVER = "https://api.telegram.org"; // Replace this with your backend URL

🔹 Step 6: Customize the UI for Your Organization

Since this chat system is only for your organization, modify UI elements:
✅ Change Telegram’s branding – Replace icons, splash screen in res/drawable.
✅ Modify user roles – Customize user permissions in UserConfig.java.
✅ Change chat layout – Customize ChatActivity.java for a unique UI.

🔹 Step 7: Testing and Deployment

1️⃣ Test Locally

  • Run your backend:
    sh
    node server.js
  • Install the app on an Android emulator or a physical device.

2️⃣ Deploy Backend

  • Use AWS, DigitalOcean, or Firebase to host your backend.
  • Deploy WebSocket API with Nginx as a reverse proxy for better performance.

3️⃣ Distribute Your App

Since this is for internal use, you don’t need to publish on Google Play. Instead,

  • Use Firebase App Distribution
  • Host APK files on a private server

🎯 Final Thoughts

✅ You are now building a completely separate chat system using Telegram’s source code, but without bot functionality and without connecting to Telegram's servers.
✅ This approach ensures privacy and customization for your organization.
✅ If you need further improvements (like end-to-end encryption, admin controls, or custom themes), you can implement them step by step.

🛠 Step-by-Step Guide with Code for Building a Custom Chat System Based on Telegram's Source Code

🔹 Step 1: Compile TDLib for Your Backend

Since TDLib is the core component, compile it for your backend.

1️⃣ Clone TDLib Source Code

sh
git clone --recursive https://github.com/tdlib/td.git
cd td

2️⃣ Install Dependencies

For Ubuntu/macOS:

sh
sudo apt update
sudo apt install cmake g++ zlib1g-dev libssl-dev libsqlite3-dev

For Windows:

  • Install MSYS2
  • Run inside MSYS2:
    sh
    pacman -S --needed base-devel mingw-w64-x86_64-toolchain

3️⃣ Build TDLib

sh
mkdir build
cd build
cmake -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release ..
cmake --build . --target install

This generates libtdjson.so (Linux/macOS) or tdjson.dll (Windows), which your Android app and backend will use.

🔹 Step 2: Modify the Android App to Remove Telegram’s Cloud & Bot Features

Now, modify Telegram's Android client to remove dependencies on Telegram’s servers and connect to your backend.

1️⃣ Remove Bot Features in TDLib

Edit TdApi.java and comment out all bot-related methods.

java
// Disable bot login
public class AuthorizationStateWaitOtherDeviceConfirmation extends AuthorizationState {
    @Override
    public boolean isUser() {
        return true;
    }
}

Remove bot-related UI elements from ChatActivity.java:

java
// Hide bot actions menu
if (user.isBot()) {
    botKeyboard.setVisibility(View.GONE);
}

2️⃣ Change API Credentials

Modify BuildVars.java to use your own API keys:

java
public static final int APP_ID = 123456; // Change this
public static final String API_HASH = "your_api_hash_here"; // Change this

🔹 You can generate APP_ID and API_HASH on my.telegram.org.

3️⃣ Replace Telegram's Backend with Your Own Server

Modify MessagesController.java to change the API URL:

java
public static String TELEGRAM_API_URL = "https://your-custom-backend.com/api/";

🔹 Step 3: Set Up Your Own Backend

Since Telegram’s backend is proprietary, you need to create your own backend server.

1️⃣ Install Node.js and Set Up WebSocket Server

sh
mkdir custom-telegram-backend && cd custom-telegram-backend
npm init -y
npm install express ws mongoose

2️⃣ Create a WebSocket Server (server.js)

javascript
const WebSocket = require("ws");
const express = require("express");
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const app = express();
const server = require("http").createServer(app);
const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ server });

mongoose.connect("mongodb://localhost:27017/chatDB", {
  useNewUrlParser: true,
  useUnifiedTopology: true
});

const MessageSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  sender: String,
  text: String,
  timestamp: Date
});
const Message = mongoose.model("Message", MessageSchema);

wss.on("connection", (ws) => {
  console.log("New client connected");

  ws.on("message", async (message) => {
    const msg = JSON.parse(message);
    const newMessage = new Message(msg);
    await newMessage.save();

    wss.clients.forEach((client) => {
      if (client.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
        client.send(JSON.stringify(newMessage));
      }
    });
  });

  ws.on("close", () => console.log("Client disconnected"));
});

server.listen(8080, () => console.log("Server running on port 8080"));

Now, your backend is ready to receive and store chat messages.

🔹 Step 4: Modify TDLib to Use Your Backend

Edit TdJsonClient.cpp in the TDLib source:

cpp
const std::string TELEGRAM_SERVER = "https://your-custom-backend.com"; // Replace Telegram server

Recompile TDLib and replace the old libtdjson.so in your Android app.

🔹 Step 5: Modify Android App to Send/Receive Messages from Your Backend

1️⃣ Connect to WebSocket Server

Modify MessagesController.java to connect to your own server:

java
import java.net.URI;
import org.java_websocket.client.WebSocketClient;
import org.java_websocket.handshake.ServerHandshake;

public class CustomWebSocketClient extends WebSocketClient {

    public CustomWebSocketClient(URI serverUri) {
        super(serverUri);
    }

    @Override
    public void onOpen(ServerHandshake handshakedata) {
        System.out.println("Connected to server");
    }

    @Override
    public void onMessage(String message) {
        System.out.println("New message: " + message);
    }

    @Override
    public void onClose(int code, String reason, boolean remote) {
        System.out.println("Connection closed");
    }

    @Override
    public void onError(Exception ex) {
        ex.printStackTrace();
    }
}

Modify ChatActivity.java to use this WebSocket client:

java
CustomWebSocketClient client = new CustomWebSocketClient(new URI("ws://your-custom-backend.com:8080"));
client.connect();

2️⃣ Send Messages via WebSockets

Modify ChatActivity.java to send messages:

java
public void sendMessage(String text) {
    JSONObject message = new JSONObject();
    message.put("sender", currentUser.getUsername());
    message.put("text", text);
    message.put("timestamp", System.currentTimeMillis());
    
    client.send(message.toString());
}

3️⃣ Receive Messages and Display in UI

Modify onMessage in CustomWebSocketClient.java:

java
@Override
public void onMessage(String message) {
    runOnUiThread(() -> {
        JSONObject msg = new JSONObject(message);
        chatAdapter.addMessage(new ChatMessage(msg.getString("sender"), msg.getString("text"), msg.getLong("timestamp")));
    });
}

🔹 Step 6: Deploy Your Backend

Deploy your backend on AWS, DigitalOcean, or Firebase.

  1. Deploy using PM2 (Process Manager)
    sh
    npm install -g pm2
pm2 start server.js --name custom-chat
  2. Use Nginx as a Reverse Proxy (on Linux):
    nginx
    server {
    listen 80;
    server_name your-custom-backend.com;
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8080;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
    }
}
  3. Restart Nginx:
    sh
    sudo systemctl restart nginx

🎯 Final Result

✅ You now have a fully customized chat system, separate from Telegram.
✅ The system removes bot functionality and stores messages on your own backend.
✅ WebSockets enable real-time messaging just like Telegram.
✅ You can customize the UI and add organization-specific features.

📌 If you haven't downloaded it yet, here’s where to get them:

  • Android App Source: https://github.com/Telegram-FOSS-Team/Telegram-FOSS
  • TDLib (Telegram Database Library): https://github.com/tdlib/td

🔹 Step 2: Compile TDLib for Your Backend

TDLib helps you handle Telegram messages but must be modified to work with your backend.

1️⃣ Install Required Dependencies

For Ubuntu/macOS:

sh
sudo apt update
sudo apt install cmake g++ zlib1g-dev libssl-dev libsqlite3-dev

For Windows:

  1. Install MSYS2
  2. Inside MSYS2, run:
    sh
    pacman -S --needed base-devel mingw-w64-x86_64-toolchain

2️⃣ Clone TDLib

sh
git clone --recursive https://github.com/tdlib/td.git
cd td

3️⃣ Build TDLib

sh
mkdir build
cd build
cmake -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release ..
cmake --build . --target install

This will generate:

  • Linux/macOS: libtdjson.so
  • Windows: tdjson.dll

🔹 Step 4: Set Up Your Own Backend

Since Telegram’s backend is private, build a custom backend.

1️⃣ Install Node.js and Set Up WebSocket Server

sh
mkdir custom-chat-backend && cd custom-chat-backend
npm init -y
npm install express ws mongoose cors dotenv

2️⃣ Create a WebSocket Server (server.js)

javascript
const WebSocket = require("ws");
const express = require("express");
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const app = express();
const server = require("http").createServer(app);
const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ server });

mongoose.connect("mongodb://localhost:27017/chatDB", {
  useNewUrlParser: true,
  useUnifiedTopology: true
});

const MessageSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  sender: String,
  text: String,
  timestamp: Date
});
const Message = mongoose.model("Message", MessageSchema);

wss.on("connection", (ws) => {
  console.log("New client connected");

  ws.on("message", async (message) => {
    const msg = JSON.parse(message);
    const newMessage = new Message(msg);
    await newMessage.save();

    wss.clients.forEach((client) => {
      if (client.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
        client.send(JSON.stringify(newMessage));
      }
    });
  });

  ws.on("close", () => console.log("Client disconnected"));
});

server.listen(8080, () => console.log("Server running on port 8080"));

✅ This stores messages in MongoDB
✅ Broadcasts messages to all connected clients in real-time

🔹 Step 6: Modify Android App to Use Your Backend

1️⃣ Connect to WebSocket Server

Modify MessagesController.java:

java
import java.net.URI;
import org.java_websocket.client.WebSocketClient;
import org.java_websocket.handshake.ServerHandshake;

public class CustomWebSocketClient extends WebSocketClient {

    public CustomWebSocketClient(URI serverUri) {
        super(serverUri);
    }

    @Override
    public void onOpen(ServerHandshake handshakedata) {
        System.out.println("Connected to server");
    }

    @Override
    public void onMessage(String message) {
        System.out.println("New message: " + message);
    }

    @Override
    public void onClose(int code, String reason, boolean remote) {
        System.out.println("Connection closed");
    }

    @Override
    public void onError(Exception ex) {
        ex.printStackTrace();
    }
}

Modify ChatActivity.java to use this WebSocket client:

java
CustomWebSocketClient client = new CustomWebSocketClient(new URI("ws://your-custom-backend.com:8080"));
client.connect();

2️⃣ Send Messages via WebSockets

Modify ChatActivity.java:

java
public void sendMessage(String text) {
    JSONObject message = new JSONObject();
    message.put("sender", currentUser.getUsername());
    message.put("text", text);
    message.put("timestamp", System.currentTimeMillis());
    
    client.send(message.toString());
}

3️⃣ Receive Messages and Display in UI

Modify onMessage in CustomWebSocketClient.java:

java
@Override
public void onMessage(String message) {
    runOnUiThread(() -> {
        JSONObject msg = new JSONObject(message);
        chatAdapter.addMessage(new ChatMessage(msg.getString("sender"), msg.getString("text"), msg.getLong("timestamp")));
    });
}

🔹 Step 7: Deploy Your Backend

1️⃣ Deploy with PM2 (Process Manager)

sh
npm install -g pm2
pm2 start server.js --name custom-chat

2️⃣ Use Nginx as a Reverse Proxy

nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name your-custom-backend.com;
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8080;
    }
}

Restart Nginx:

sh
sudo systemctl restart nginx
